CALL FOR PAPERS

---------------------------------------------------------------------------=
------------------------------------------------------------

DIGITAL HUMANITIES AND ICONOGRAPHY -

THE CASE OF ALPINE MURAL PAINTING


28 & 29 November 2016

Maison des Sciences de l=E2=80=99Homme =E2=80=93 Grenoble =E2=80=93 France


web site: hn2016en.condillac.org


Deadline for submission of abstracts: 2 June 2016

Notification to authors: 21 July 2016


The international conference "Digital Humanities and Iconography - The case
of alpine mural painting", to be held in Grenoble (France) from 28 to 29
November 2016, is organised by the University of Grenoble-Alpes (Maison des
Sciences de l=E2=80=99Homme) and the University of Savoie Mont Blanc (Condi=
llac
Research Group - LISTIC lab).


As part of the discussions conducted at the Maison des Sciences de l=E2=80=
=99Homme
Sciences-Alpes on the links between Digital Humanities and Heritage, this
international symposium, resolutely turned towards the future, aims to
debate one particular aspect: how to "intelligently" access the data. How
can digitised and scientifically validated data in the field of Social
Sciences and Humanities be made available to a wider audience, that will
not only share but also diversify its uses? There will be two pivotal
topics under discussion: on the one hand, the need to respect the
linguistic diversity involved in the development and description of such
data. On the other hand, the need to consider the multiplicity of
approaches that have presided over the conceptual modelling of the data in
question.

To meet these objectives, without excluding other iconographic sources, we
draw the emphasis on case studies on the murals of the Alpine regions from
the thirteenth to the sixteenth centuries in the PREALP database, hosted at
the MSH-Alpes.


Three areas have been selected: language - concepts - images. Particular
attention will be given to reflections on the contribution of terminology
to address the linguistic dimension, of ontology for the conceptual
dimension, and of image recognition for the selection and classification of
iconographic material.

This conference is also an opportunity to establish an international
network of researchers to meet the challenges of a rapidly changing field.


Paper proposals (800 words maximum), in French, English or Italian, which
will be the three working languages of the conference, should be sent to
the organising committee:


Dominique Rigaux (dominique.rigaux@msh-alpes.fr)

Christophe Roche (christophe.roche@univ-savoie.fr)


